		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9038'>Mister</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR> <font class="afont">( was very helpful )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">Heh, looks like you beat me to the punch on writing a Multiplayer politics article. I think that most of your ideas(particularly the players&#39; personalities) might work in low-level play, but at medium to upper division competition I am skeptical of its application. From experience, most of the better players try to keep their motives hidden(although we ALL though their goal is to win the game, and ultimately the tournament). You may get new/casual players in the fray, but these people tend to be fed to the wolves. Since Multiplayer Lord of the Rings games are 3 player or 4 player games, in the former it is very likely that 2 players will realize that it is to their advantage to eliminate the other player. In the latter, the case is likely to be that the game turns to a 2v2 team game, with the first team to get a player eliminated probably losing the match. Now, for what the remaining two players do after the enemy is gone, you have to play your cards reasonably conservatively(as to not look like you&#39;re holding back, but you have to keep enough firepower to wipe out your ex-partner when the time comes, OR you need to move far enough in the path(and keep every else&#39;s attention off of you) that you can waltz to site 9). I think you address the "situational awareness" well enough. However, I disagree with some of our points on the syngery section. Moria still has the best synergy(with itself and others). Overwhelming Frodo seems to be the key way to kill in Multiplayer, since you have to wait 2-3 turns to get back to the player it is likely that either you(and/or the other players) have likely played out their different cards against another so the next attack against a player will probably be a mixed bag of minions or it&#39;ll be a different culture. If you hit them with Uruk-Hai for +1 Damage, them it would be more efficient to kill them by wounding with more +1 Damage attacks as opposed another player wasting Goblins to overwhelming him. I can explain my rationale in greater detail later. I&#39;ve been working on a Multiplayer politics article myself, but I&#39;ve never gotten around to finishing it. This guide will serve well enough at lower to some medium level tournaments, but at higher levels of competitive play the politics become a LOT more complex and convuluted. Great article!  <font size=1>(+4 tp, Double-Edged Sword)</font><BR>
		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=3035'>Anime Knight</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR> <font class="afont">( was very helpful )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">great article, but a little too elaborated on the personalities, which is probably the more irrelevent section.  still great article with some good ideas and a lot of time spent.  <font size=1>(+2 tp)</font><BR>
		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9659'>zextydark</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR> <font class="afont">( was very helpful )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">I think you depend on reading your opponents too much. Provided you&#39;re in a big competition environment, if you&#39;re winning, you&#39;re going to be playing other opponents who know also how to read people and will utilize poke faces. Although you may be able which type to tell they aren&#39;t, I don&#39;t think you&#39;ll necessarily be able to tell what they are. I think you missed mentioning some dynamics and strategies that would aid people. The discussion what you need to know to protect yourself in multi player is good, but I felt your offensive discussion was somewhat lacking. I still liked your analysis of opponents though. Great job.  <font size=1>(+2 tp)</font><BR>
